The intent of this license is simple: SnapDock is free for individuals running
it at home, for students learning from it, and for educators teaching with it.
If you are using it to make money — whether by selling it, offering it as a
service, or building a commercial product on top of it — you need to ask first.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SECTION 1 — DEFINITIONS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1.1 "Software" means the SnapDock source code, compiled binaries, Docker images,
    documentation, and any associated materials made available under this license.

1.2 "Personal Use" means use by a single individual on hardware they personally
    own or rent, exclusively for their own non-commercial benefit. This includes
    self-hosting SnapDock in a home lab environment to manage containers running
    on personal servers, NAS devices, Raspberry Pi clusters, or similar equipment.

1.3 "Educational Use" means use by students, teachers, or researchers within an
    academic institution (school, college, university, or coding bootcamp) for
    learning, teaching, coursework, research papers, or academic demonstrations.
    This includes use in open-source academic projects published without charge.

1.4 "Non-Commercial Open-Source Use" means use within a software project that
    is (a) published under an OSI-approved open-source license, (b) not sold or
    monetised in any form, and (c) does not generate revenue for any individual
    or organisation, directly or indirectly.

1.5 "Commercial Use" means any use not covered by Sections 1.2, 1.3, or 1.4
    above, including but not limited to:
      (a) running SnapDock as part of a paid product or paid service;
      (b) running SnapDock internally within a for-profit company or organisation,
          even if SnapDock itself is not sold;
      (c) offering SnapDock or a derivative of it as a hosted or managed service
          (SaaS, PaaS, or similar) to any third party, whether for payment or free;
      (d) embedding SnapDock into a commercial product or commercial distribution;
      (e) using SnapDock to generate revenue, directly or indirectly, for any
          individual, company, or organisation.

1.6 "Derivative Work" means any work that incorporates, modifies, extends, forks,
    or builds upon the Software in any material way.

1.7 "Licensor" means Fahim Ahmed, the copyright holder of the Software.

